Hawai'i's same-sex marriage bill, and stories of Indigenous women falling in love with non-human beings such as animals, plants, and stars. Following the politics of gender, sexuality, and feminism across these diverse historical and cultural contexts, the contributors question and reframe the thinking about Indigenous knowledge, nationhood, citizenship, history, identity, belonging, and the possibilities for a decolonial future.Contributors. Jodi A. Byrd, Joanne Barker, Jennifer Nez Denetdale, Mishuana Goeman, J. Kēhaulani Kauanui, Melissa K. Nelson, Jessica Bissett Perea, Mark Rifkin  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aDecolonizationzUnited States. 0aFeminist theory. 0aIndians of North AmericaxHistoriography. 0aIndigenous peoples in literature. 0aIndigenous peoplesxHistoriography. 0aQueer theory. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aBarker, Joanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373162zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822373162.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles